    <string name="date_format_placeholders_help_title">You can use the following placeholders (example in brackets)</string>
    <string name="date_format_placeholders_help">
    G - Era designator (AD)\n
    yyyy or yy - Year (2024 or 24)\n
    MM or MMM or MMMM - Month (12 or Dec or December)\n
    ww - Week in year (27)\n
    W - Week in month (2)\n
    DDD - Day in year (189)\n
    d or dd - Day in month (1 or 01)\n
    F - Day of week in month (2)\n
    EEEE or E - Week day name (Monday or Mon.)\n
    u - Day number of week (1-7)\n
    a - AM/PM marker\n
    HH - Hour in day (0-23)\n
    hh - Hour in AM/PM (1-12)\n
    mm - Minute in hour\n
    ss - Second in minute\n
    zzzz or z - Time zone name (Pacific Standard Time or PST)\n
    Z - RFC 822 time zone (-0800)\n
    XXX or X - RFC 8601 time zone (-08:00 or -08)\n\n
    Custom text can be added in single quotes, e.g. \'your text\'.
    </string>
